# Injecting Collection Data Types

Spring also supports injection of Collection properties.

Supported Collections:

- List
- Set
- Map

---

## Collection Tags

| Collection | Spring Tag |
|------------|------------|
| List | `<list>` |
| Set | `<set>` |
| Map | `<map>` |

---

# Injecting List Property

## Bean Property

```java
private List<String> emails;
```

---

## XML Configuration

```xml
<property name="emails">

    <list>
        <value>dilip@gmail.com</value>
        <value>laxmi@gmail.com</value>
        <value>dilip@gmail.com</value>
    </list>

</property>
```

---

## Result

```text
[dilip@gmail.com,
 laxmi@gmail.com,
 dilip@gmail.com]
```

### Observation

```text
List allows duplicate values.
```

---

# Injecting Set Property

## Bean Property

```java
private Set<String> mobileNumbers;
```

---

## XML Configuration

```xml
<property name="mobileNumbers">

    <set>
        <value>8826111377</value>
        <value>8826111377</value>
        <value>+1234567890</value>
    </set>

</property>
```

---

## Result

```text
[8826111377,
 +1234567890]
```

### Observation

```text
Set automatically removes duplicate values.
```

Duplicate:

```text
8826111377
```

stored only once.

---

# Injecting Map Property

## Bean Property

```java
private Map<String,String> subMarks;
```

---

## XML Configuration

```xml
<property name="subMarks">

    <map>

        <entry key="maths"
               value="88"/>

        <entry key="science"
               value="66"/>

        <entry key="english"
               value="44"/>

    </map>

</property>
```

---

## Result

```text
{
 maths=88,
 science=66,
 english=44
}
```

---

## Understanding Map Injection

### key

Represents Map Key.

Example:

```xml
key="maths"
```

---

### value

Represents Map Value.

Example:

```xml
value="88"
```

---

# Complete Bean Configuration

```xml
<bean id="studentOne"
      class="com.naresh.hello.Student">

    <property name="stuName" value="Dilip"/>
    <property name="studId" value="101"/>
    <property name="avgOfMarks" value="99.88"/>
    <property name="passedOutYear" value="2022"/>
    <property name="isSelected" value="true"/>

    <property name="emails">
        <list>
            <value>dilip@gmail.com</value>
            <value>laxmi@gmail.com</value>
            <value>dilip@gmail.com</value>
        </list>
    </property>

    <property name="mobileNumbers">
        <set>
            <value>8826111377</value>
            <value>8826111377</value>
            <value>+1234567890</value>
        </set>
    </property>

    <property name="subMarks">
        <map>
            <entry key="maths" value="88"/>
            <entry key="science" value="66"/>
            <entry key="english" value="44"/>
        </map>
    </property>

</bean>
```

---

# Complete Output

```text
101
Dilip
2022
99.88
true

[dilip@gmail.com,
 laxmi@gmail.com,
 dilip@gmail.com]

[8826111377,
 +1234567890]

{maths=88,
 science=66,
 english=44}
```

---

# Internal Flow

```text
beans.xml
      ↓
Spring Reads Bean Configuration
      ↓
Creates Student Object
      ↓
Injects Primitive Values
      ↓
Injects String Values
      ↓
Injects List Values
      ↓
Injects Set Values
      ↓
Injects Map Values
      ↓
Stores Bean In IoC Container
      ↓
getBean("studentOne")
      ↓
Returns Fully Configured Object
```

---

# Key Points

- Primitive values are injected using `<property>` tag.
- String values are injected using `<property>` tag.
- `name` attribute represents Bean variable name.
- `value` attribute represents actual value to be injected.
- `<list>` is used for List injection.
- `<set>` is used for Set injection.
- `<map>` is used for Map injection.
- List allows duplicate values.
- Set removes duplicate values.
- Map stores data as Key-Value pairs.
- Spring performs injection through setter methods.

---

# Quick Revision

| Property Type | XML Tag |
|--------------|----------|
| Primitive | `<property>` |
| String | `<property>` |
| List | `<list>` |
| Set | `<set>` |
| Map | `<map>` |

---

## Conclusion

Spring Setter Injection can inject primitive data types, String values, and Collection data types into Bean objects using XML configuration. Collection injection is supported through `<list>`, `<set>`, and `<map>` tags, allowing Spring to create fully configured Bean objects inside the IoC Container.
